{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a27ec9e-6a77-47a2-b1a9-b3d466540401","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, so here's the general guidance from .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** The OS writes a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, check:\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   You may need to create `/cores` and fix permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (Xcode CLI tools):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 -- ./MyApp\n   ```\n   Inside lldb: `bt` for backtrace, `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n\n6. **For managed stack traces**, load the SOS/dotnet diagnostics plugin in lldb:\n   ```bash\n   plugin load /path/to/libsosplugin.dylib\n   sos clrstack\n   ```\n\n> **Key point:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` because there's no CoreCLR runtime. You rely on the OS-level core dump mechanism (`/cores`) and `lldb` instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"50f1e0d2-b6d7-4cb0-b65f-77a8bbc6fd28","outputTokens":377,"requestId":"AC0A:2E3AFD:13EC726:1664C8B:6A0671F8"},"id":"c7edeef5-5e75-4ca5-91a1-044deebaa337","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:08:17.803Z","parentId":"78b02d2c-def8-4b0f-a9fb-75692fe17f27"}
